<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837889000035&r=1&w=2">Gratuitous use of the domain system</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784000011&r=1&w=2">David C. Plummer &lt;DCP () QUABBIN ! SCRC ! Symbolics ! COM&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198710">1987-10-22 10:31:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926958&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926958&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I know I can technically store other information in the domain system.
Because classes and types are bit-packed fields, I have to coordinate
with the Number Czar to make sure I'm not interfering with anybody else.
There isn't a range of experimental numbers.  And as you say, you need
to make extensions to the server.  Once experimental new types/classes
are made into RFCs, the format is pretty much frozen because of the
difficulty in having flag-days for switchovers.  That is one of my
complaints about bit-packed, and binary and binary-structured data.

